{
    <span class="tok-comment">// DFS uses a stack for LIFO checking — commits down one branch</span>
    <span class="tok-comment">// before backtracking, producing long, winding paths</span>
    <span class="tok-type">Stack</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt;                  <span class="tok-param">open</span>     = <span class="tok-keyword">new</span> <span class="tok-type">Stack</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt;();
    <span class="tok-type">Dictionary</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>, <span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt; <span class="tok-param">cameFrom</span> = <span class="tok-keyword">new</span> <span class="tok-type">Dictionary</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>, <span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt;();

    <span class="tok-param">open</span>.<span class="tok-method">Push</span>(<span class="tok-param">start</span>);
    <span class="tok-param">cameFrom</span>[<span class="tok-param">start</span>] = <span class="tok-param">start</span>;

    <span class="tok-keyword">while</span> (<span class="tok-param">open</span>.Count &gt; <span class="tok-num">0</span>)
    {
        <span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span> <span class="tok-param">current</span> = <span class="tok-param">open</span>.<span class="tok-method">Pop</span>();
        <span class="tok-keyword">if</span> (<span class="tok-param">current</span> == <span class="tok-param">end</span>) <span class="tok-keyword">break</span>;

        <span class="tok-comment">// Shuffle before pushing so each run takes a different route</span>
        <span class="tok-type">List</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt; <span class="tok-param">neighbours</span> = <span class="tok-method">GetNeighboursTowards</span>(<span class="tok-param">current</span>, <span class="tok-param">end</span>);
        <span class="tok-param">neighbours</span> = <span class="tok-method">Shuffle</span>(<span class="tok-param">neighbours</span>);

        <span class="tok-keyword">foreach</span> (<span class="tok-keyword">var</span> <span class="tok-param">direction</span> <span class="tok-keyword">in</span> <span class="tok-param">neighbours</span>)
        {
            <span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span> <span class="tok-param">newDir</span> = <span class="tok-param">current</span> + <span class="tok-param">direction</span>;

            <span class="tok-keyword">if</span> (!<span class="tok-method">IsInsideGrid</span>(<span class="tok-param">newDir</span>) || <span class="tok-param">newDir</span>.y != <span class="tok-num">0</span> || <span class="tok-param">cameFrom</span>.<span class="tok-method">ContainsKey</span>(<span class="tok-param">newDir</span>))
                <span class="tok-keyword">continue</span>;

            <span class="tok-param">open</span>.<span class="tok-method">Push</span>(<span class="tok-param">newDir</span>);
            <span class="tok-param">cameFrom</span>[<span class="tok-param">newDir</span>] = <span class="tok-param">current</span>;
        }
    }

    <span class="tok-keyword">if</span> (!<span class="tok-param">cameFrom</span>.<span class="tok-method">ContainsKey</span>(<span class="tok-param">end</span>))
        <span class="tok-keyword">return</span> <span class="tok-keyword">null</span>;

    <span class="tok-comment">// Rebuild path backwards from end → start, then reverse</span>
    <span class="tok-type">List</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt; <span class="tok-param">path</span>          = <span class="tok-keyword">new</span> <span class="tok-type">List</span>&lt;<span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>&gt;();
    <span class="tok-type">Vector3Int</span>        <span class="tok-param">currentReverse</span> = <span class="tok-param">end</span>;

    <span class="tok-keyword">while</span> (<span class="tok-param">currentReverse</span> != <span class="tok-param">start</span>)
    {
        <span class="tok-param">path</span>.<span class="tok-method">Add</span>(<span class="tok-param">currentReverse</span>);
        <span class="tok-param">currentReverse</span> = <span class="tok-param">cameFrom</span>[<span class="tok-param">currentReverse</span>];
    }

    <span class="tok-param">path</span>.<span class="tok-method">Add</span>(<span class="tok-param">start</span>);
    <span class="tok-param">path</span>.<span class="tok-method">Reverse</span>();
    <span class="tok-keyword">return</span> <span class="tok-param">path</span>;
}`;
---

<BaseLayout title="WFC Generator - Jonathan To">
  <div slot="breadcrumb" class="breadcrumb-bar">
    <a href="/personal-projects/">PersonalProjects()</a>
    <span class="breadcrumb-sep">/</span>
    <span class="breadcrumb-current">WFC_Generator</span>
  </div>

  <ProjectHeader
    title="WFC Generator"
    subtitle="Procedural Generation · Pathfinding (BFS + DFS)"
    tags={[
      { label: "Programming", type: "programming" },
      { label: "Unity", type: "unity" },
    ]}
    description="A procedural 2D map generator using Wave Function Collapse, with optional pathfinding support."
  />

  <VideoEmbed
    videoId="7own_IyHZts"
    caption="// fig_01 - Main gameplay screenshot · JellyFish"
    alt="JellyFish Trailer"
  />

  <div class="grid gap-6" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 260px;">
    <TextBlock
      title="Overview"
      content="A solo personal project exploring procedural generation and pathfinding. The generator uses
        Wave Function Collapse to produce valid, constraint-satisfying 2D tile maps, with an optional
        pathfinding layer - supporting both BFS and DFS - that can overlay single or multiple paths
        across the generated output."
    />

    <TextBlock
      title="Contributions"
      content={[
        "Wave Function Collapse system - tile architecture built on ScriptableObjects and enum-defined face rules, with weighted randomness for tile selection",
        "Flexible pathfinding layer - integrated BFS and DFS algorithms with added randomization to produce natural, varied paths",
        "Multi-path support - extended pathfinding to handle multiple overlapping paths across a single generated map, enabling more complex interconnected layouts",
      ]}
    />

    <div style="grid-column:2; grid-row:1/3;">
      <ProjectDetails
        meta={[
          { key: "status", value: "complete", highlight: true },
          { key: "year", value: "2024" },
          { key: "duration", value: "3 months" },
          { key: "team_size", value: "1 (solo)" },
          { key: "platform", value: "PC" },
          { key: "context", value: "Personal / Educational" },
        ]}
        links={[
          {
            label: "View on GitHub",
            href: "https://github.com/JonTo212/Wave-Function-Collapse-Generator",
            icon: "◇",
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:1rem;">
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--bg-panel);">
      <div
        style="padding:10px 16px; background:var(--bg-card); border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); font-family:'Commit Mono',monospace; font-size:1.1rem; color:var(--green-dim);"
      >
        // Key Features
      </div>
    </div>

    <KeyFeature
      index={1}
      title="Wave Function Collapse"
      description="A constraint-based WFC system that builds maps by progressively reducing possibilities across a grid.
        Every cell starts with a full set of valid tiles; the generator collapses the lowest-entropy cell first,
        then propagates adjacency constraints through a queue until the entire grid resolves.
        Tile data and adjacency rules are defined via ScriptableObjects with directional face enums, keeping
        the system scalable and easy to extend. Tile selection supports weighted randomness, allowing
        certain tiles to appear more frequently while preserving procedural variety."
      imageSrc="/images/wfc-generator/wfc-wfc.png"
      snippetLabel="WFCTileGenerator.cs - Propagate"
      snippetFilename="WFCTileGenerator.cs"
      snippetCode={propagateSnippetPlain}
      flip={true}
    >
      <pre
        slot="snippet-code"
        style="margin:0; padding:1.25rem 1.5rem; overflow-x:auto; background:var(--bg); font-size:12px; line-height:1.8; white-space:pre-wrap; word-break:break-word;"><code class="font-mono text-(--text-code)" set:html={propagateSnippetHtml} /></pre>
    </KeyFeature>

    <KeyFeature
      index={2}
      title="Pathfinding"
      description="BFS and DFS are both supported, each producing paths with a distinct character.
        BFS explores level-by-level via a FIFO queue - neighbours sorted by distance to target -
        guaranteeing the shortest route. DFS commits depth-first via a LIFO stack, producing longer,
        more winding paths. Neighbour order is shuffled before every DFS push, so routes vary
        each run and feel hand-placed rather than deterministic. Multiple overlapping paths resolve
        through a shared connection dictionary: each tile selects its type based on connection count,
        turning one into a dead end, two into a segment, and three or more into a junction -
        no hardcoded rules required."
      imageGridLayout="offset"
      imageGrid={[
        {
          src: "/images/wfc-generator/wfc-bfs.png",
          caption: "BFS - shortest path",
        },
        {
          src: "/images/wfc-generator/wfc-dfs.png",
          caption: "DFS - winding path",
        },
        {
          src: "/images/wfc-generator/wfc-multi-path-bfs.png",
          caption: "DFS w/ randomization + BFS",
        },
        {
          src: "/images/wfc-generator/wfc-multi-path-reg.png",
          caption: "multi-path junctions",
        },
      ]}
      snippetLabel="WFCTileGenerator.cs - DFSWithRandomization"
      snippetFilename="WFCTileGenerator.cs"
      snippetCode={dfsSnippetPlain}
    >
      <pre
        slot="snippet-code"
        style="margin:0; padding:1.25rem 1.5rem; overflow-x:auto; background:var(--bg); font-size:12px; line-height:1.8; white-space:pre-wrap; word-break:break-word;"><code class="font-mono text-(--text-code)" set:html={dfsSnippetHtml} /></pre>
    </KeyFeature>

    <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:2rem;">
      <DeepDiveBlock
        title="Deep dive - adding pathfinding with multiple path support"
        steps={[
          {
            tag: "problem",
            icon: "◎",
            title: "Path lists don't cleanly connect",
            body: "The end of one path and the start of the next were often more than 1 unit apart. The collapse function expects every neighbour to be exactly 1 unit away, so any larger gap left a tile with no valid solution - resulting in a broken, uncollapsable tile at the junction.",
          },
          {
            tag: "approach",
            icon: "◈",
            title: "Adding an additional validation layer",
            body: "Instead of collapsing path lists directly, I first build a dictionary of every grid point and its valid connections. IsFaceNeighbour validates that each tile is exactly 1 unit from its neighbours before it gets added. AddConnections then loops through all paths to populate the dictionary, using a HashSet per entry to avoid duplicate connections. Only then does the collapse run, using each tile's connection count to select the correct tile type.",
          },
          {
            tag: "result",
            icon: "▸",
            title: "Validated junction resolution",
            body: "Paths of any count can now be combined and collapsed without broken junctions. Each tile resolves based on its connection count - tiles with one connection become ends, two form straight segments, and three or more create junctions. Overlapping paths emerge naturally without any hardcoded rules.",
          },
        ]}
        slider={{
          label: "path_junction_fix",
          beforeSrc: "",
          afterSrc: "",
        }}
      />

      <TextBlock
        title="Takeaways"
        content={[
          {
            heading: "Deeper learning through integration",
            body: "Working with multiple algorithms together, rather than studying each in isolation, forced a deeper understanding of how each works - the modifications required for them to operate in tandem surfaced edge cases that studying them separately never would have.",
          },
          {
            heading: "The power of constraints",
            body: "Just like in game design, a small set of well-defined rules can produce a huge range of outcomes. Procedural generation takes that idea and runs with it - simple adjacency constraints scaling into a genuinely varied map generator.",
          },
          {
            heading: "A worthwhile investment",
            body: "There's a steep learning curve getting into algorithmic thinking, but the payoff is real. This project made clear that algorithms aren't single-purpose solutions - they have the potential to produce a wide variety of results depending on how they're applied.",
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

    <ProjectFooter
      prev={{ label: "Ronin Run", href: "../ronin-run/" }}
      next={{ label: "Deterministic Dice", href: "../deterministic-dice/" }}
      author="Jonathan To · Gameplay Programmer & Game Designer"
      year={2026}
    />
  </div></BaseLayout
>
